The exact date of Kifune Shrine’s founding is unknown. From the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft}} onward, the shrine known as Takada Shrine declined, and its precise location was lost.
During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft}}, a debate arose over whether the historic Takada Shrine was actually Kifune Shrine in Koreju, Furukawa-go, or the Hakusan Shrine in Oe, Furukawa-go. The correct reading of the name 高田神社 should be "Agata Shrine" (あがたじんじゃ), but it was mistakenly read as "Takada Shrine" (たかだじんじゃ). Supporters of Kifune Shrine pointed to the local place name "Takada" (字高田) as evidence that it had been a sacred site, arguing that this indicated Kifune Shrine was the true Takada Shrine.
