== History ==
The exact date of Kifune Shrine’s founding is unknown. From the [[:en:Muromachi period|Muromachi period]] onward, the shrine known as Takada Shrine declined, and its precise location was lost.
During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], a debate arose over whether the historic Takada Shrine was actually Kifune Shrine in Koreju, Furukawa-go, or the Hakusan Shrine in Oe, Furukawa-go. The correct reading of the name 高田神社 should be "Agata Shrine" (あがたじんじゃ), but it was mistakenly read as "Takada Shrine" (たかだじんじゃ). Supporters of Kifune Shrine pointed to the local place name "Takada" (字高田) as evidence that it had been a sacred site, arguing that this indicated Kifune Shrine was the true Takada Shrine.
This debate was settled in the [[:en:Bunka|Bunka era]] when the {{ill|Yoshida family (Shinto)|ja|吉田家|1=Urabe clan|2=ja|3=卜部氏|lt=Yoshida family|comment=Might be more of a redirect with potential but this is strictly potential right now|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshida family (Shinto)|qq=}}, a prominent Shinto priestly family, identified Hakusan Shrine in Oe as the true site of Takada Shrine. The shrine was accordingly renamed Takada Shrine. However, Kifune Shrine's claim remained strong, and in [[:en:1869|Meiji 2]][[Category:Years needing redirect replacements]] (1869), an investigation by Takayama Prefecture found the location of Takada Shrine to be "unverified." It was not until [[:en:1870|Meiji 3]][[Category:Years needing redirect replacements]] (1870) that the Hakusan Shrine was officially recognized as the true Takada Shrine.
Although Kifune Shrine was not renamed Takada Shrine, it remains recognized as a possible location (論社) for the historical Takada Shrine.
